==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sore
<hw>Sore</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A young hawk or
falcon in the first year.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A young buck in the fourth year.
See the Note under <er>Buck</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sore
<hw>Sore</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Sorer</adjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Sorest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sor</ets>, <ets>sar</ets>,
AS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧r</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zeer</ets>, OS. & OHG.
<ets>s<?/r</ets>, G. <ets>sehr</ets> very, Icel. <ets>s⟦amac⟧rr</ets>,
Sw. <ets>s⟦aring⟧r</ets>, Goth. <ets>sair</ets> pain. Cf.
<er>Sorry</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Tender to the touch; susceptible
of pain from pressure; inflamed; painful; -- said of the body or its
parts; <as>as, a <ex>sore</ex> hand</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Sensitive; tender; easily pained, grieved, or
vexed; very susceptible of irritation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Malice and hatred are very fretting and vexatious, and apt to make
our minds <qex>sore</qex> and uneasy.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Severe; afflictive; distressing; <as>as, a
<ex>sore</ex> disease; <ex>sore</ex> evil or calamity</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Criminal; wrong; evil.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sore throat</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>inflammation
of the throat and tonsils; pharyngitis. See <er>Cynanche</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Malignant sore throat</b></col>, <col><b>Ulcerated sore
throat</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Putrid sore
throat</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Angina</er>, and under
<er>Putrid</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sore
<hw>Sore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sor</ets>,
<ets>sar</ets>, AS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧r</ets>. See <er>Sore</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place in an animal body where
the skin and flesh are ruptured or bruised, so as to be tender or
painful; a painful or diseased place, such as an ulcer or a
boil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The dogs came and licked his <qex>sores</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Luke
xvi. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Grief; affliction; trouble; difficulty.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see plainly where his <qex>sore</qex> lies.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gold sore</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Gold</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Sore
<hw>Sore</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>s⟦amac⟧re</ets>. See
<er>Sore</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a sore manner;
with pain; grievously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy hand presseth me <qex>sore</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxxviii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Greatly; violently; deeply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Hannah] prayed unto the Lord and wept <qex>sore</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>1 Sam. i. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sore</qex> sighed the knight, who this long sermon heard.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soredia</ent>⟦br⟧
